#compdef optimizt
# =============================================================================
# optimizt — FunBox's "CLI image optimization tool" — a
#          Node.js multi-format image optimization CLI
#          designed for the dual-pass workflow of (1)
#          losslessly recompressing existing PNG/JPEG/GIF/
#          SVG assets in place AND (2) generating modern
#          AVIF + WebP companions alongside each original,
#          producing the <picture>-element-ready triplets
#          that modern Web Performance budgets require.
#          Distinguishing from imagemin (Sindre Sorhus's
#          ecosystem of single-format optimizer plugins
#          glued together via imagemin's plugin protocol),
#          squoosh-cli (the GoogleChromeLabs Squoosh
#          web-app's CLI counterpart, currently
#          unmaintained), tinypng-cli (commercial
#          TinyPNG-API wrappers), sharp-cli (Lovell
#          Fuller's standalone sharp CLI for size/format
#          conversion), gulp-imagemin (gulp pipeline
#          plugin), and oxipng (Rust-only PNG optimizer)
#          by:
#            - SHARP-NATIVE BACKEND — uses lovell/sharp
#              v0.30 (libvips-bindings) as the headline
#              image library (this is the headline CLI
#              library that CLOSES Axis 40 on the TS-Node
#              side at 1/1/1; see taxonomy notes below)
#              for AVIF + WebP generation from JPEG/PNG
#              sources.  libvips is the fastest open-
#              source image processing library available;
#              orders of magnitude faster than ImageMagick
#              for batch operations
#            - GUETZLI for JPEG — uses Google's Guetzli
#              encoder (via funbox/guetzli-bin) for
#              perceptually-tuned JPEG recompression;
#              produces JPEGs that look identical at
#              dramatically smaller byte sizes than
#              libjpeg-turbo defaults
#            - SVGO for SVG — uses svgo v2.6 for SVG
#              optimization (path simplification,
#              attribute deduplication, plugin pipeline);
#              preserves visual fidelity while removing
#              redundant XML
#            - GIFSICLE for GIF — uses Eddie Kohler's
#              gifsicle (via gifsicle npm wrapper) for
#              animated GIF optimization (palette
#              quantization, frame deduplication)
#            - GIF2WEBP for ANIMATED GIF → ANIMATED WEBP
#              — uses gif2webp-bin (wrapper around Google's
#              libwebp gif2webp tool) to convert animated
#              GIFs into the smaller + higher-quality
#              animated WebP format
#            - PICTURE-ELEMENT WORKFLOW — `--avif` +
#              `--webp` modes generate `image.avif` +
#              `image.webp` alongside `image.jpg` so a
#              `<picture>` element can serve the AVIF to
#              modern browsers, fall back to WebP for
#              Safari + older Chrome, and fall back to
#              the original JPEG for Internet Explorer +
#              very old browsers
#            - PARALLEL OPTIMIZATION via p-limit — uses
#              p-limit to bound concurrent optimizations
#              to a reasonable number based on CPU count;
#              processes 100s of images simultaneously
#              without exhausting file descriptors or RAM
#            - PROGRESS BAR via cli-progress — shows
#              real-time progress + ETA + bytes-saved
#              counters for long batch jobs
#            - GLOB SUPPORT via fast-glob — accepts
#              directory paths AND glob patterns
#              (`src/**/*.png`); fast-glob is the
#              fastest pure-JS glob library
#            - LOSSLESS MODE — `-l` / `--lossless` flag
#              switches all optimizers to lossless
#              settings; useful for archival assets +
#              logos + UI sprites where any visual change
#              is unacceptable
#            - VERBOSE MODE — `-v` / `--verbose` prints
#              per-file before/after byte sizes + percent
#              savings; useful for CI pipelines that
#              want to log optimization effectiveness
#            - CUSTOM CONFIG — `-c <path>` / `--config
#              <path>` overrides the default configuration
#              (encoder quality settings, plugin lists);
#              suitable for projects with specific
#              quality vs filesize tradeoffs
#            - OUTPUT-TO-DIR — `-o <path>` / `--output
#              <path>` writes optimized output to a
#              separate directory instead of in-place,
#              preserving the original tree structure;
#              useful for CI pipelines that want to
#              compare before/after side-by-side
#            - FORCE MODE — `-f` / `--force` skips the
#              "would result in larger file" check that
#              normally aborts optimization when the
#              optimizer's output would be bigger than
#              the input (e.g. a fully-optimized PNG)
#            - 945+ STARS ON funbox/optimizt — backed by
#              FunBox (funbox.ru), the Russian software
#              studio behind iFunny mobile app + numerous
#              open-source web tools.  Active maintenance
#          Used by: Web frontend teams adopting
#          <picture>-element responsive images for
#          Web Performance + Core Web Vitals; static-
#          site generators (Hugo / Jekyll / Eleventy)
#          post-build steps that need to optimize
#          generated assets; CI/CD pipelines that
#          auto-optimize committed assets via pre-
#          commit hooks; e-commerce sites with large
#          product-image catalogs needing batch
#          optimization across formats.
#
# Author:  FunBox (https://funbox.ru) — Russian software
#          studio.  Maintained under the funbox GitHub
#          organization; package published as
#          @funboxteam/optimizt on npm.
# Source:  https://github.com/funbox/optimizt
#          https://github.com/funbox/optimizt/blob/main/cli.js
#          https://github.com/funbox/optimizt/blob/main/package.json
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `optimizt --help`
#          shows the option list (commander's auto-
#          generated help).  Full docs in repo README.md.
# Library: sharp ^0.30.4 (lovell/sharp — Lovell Fuller's
